The simultaneous closure of the Strait of Hormuz (de facto operational since March 4, 2026) and the Bab el-Mandeb Strait — threatened by Iran's Axis of Resistance as of April 2026 — would constitute the largest maritime supply disruption in recorded history, blocking up to 25% of global oil and gas supply. India, as the world's third-largest oil importer and a nation with 85%+ crude import dependency, faces multi-domain exposure across energy, food, pharmaceuticals, manufacturing, financial markets, and diplomatic positioning.

This report assesses the strategic, economic, diplomatic, and systemic risks to India arising from a full or near-full closure of the Bab el-Mandeb Strait — the 29-km-wide 'Gate of Tears' between Yemen and Djibouti — compounded by the existing Strait of Hormuz blockade. Drawing on scenario analysis, stress-testing across economic variables, and multi-domain impact modelling, this document is intended to inform senior policymakers, strategic planners, and institutional investors.
The analysis proceeds in four structural parts: (1) Strategic Context and Threat Characterization; (2) Scenario Analysis Framework; (3) Sectoral and Systemic Impact Assessment across twelve dimensions; and (4) India's Diplomatic Posture and Probable Alignments. Each section is supported by quantitative estimates, comparative historical references, and probability-weighted outcome ranges.

