SECTION I: STRATEGIC CONTEXT & THREAT CHARACTERISATION

1.1  The Bab el-Mandeb: Geography and Strategic Weight
The Bab el-Mandeb Strait — from Arabic meaning 'Gate of Tears' — is a 29-km-wide maritime chokepoint separating Yemen to the northeast from Djibouti and Eritrea on the southwestern African shore. Bisected by Yemen's Perim (Mayun) Island into two navigational channels, it serves as the southern gateway to the Red Sea, which in turn connects via the Suez Canal to the Mediterranean and European markets. It is, in effect, the hinge of the Asia-Europe trade arc.
