1.2  The 2026 Crisis: Concurrent Chokepoint Stress
The current crisis emerged from the February 28, 2026 US-Israeli Operation Epic Fury — coordinated airstrikes on Iranian military, nuclear, and leadership infrastructure — including the assassination of Supreme Leader Ali Khamenei. Iran's response included the progressive closure of the Strait of Hormuz, which, from March 4, 2026, became effectively shut to vessels from the US, Israel, and their Western allies. By April 18, Iran re-declared Hormuz closed in response to a US counter-blockade of Iranian ports.
DOUBLE CHOKEPOINT SCENARIO — DECLARED, NOT SPECULATIVE
Iran's former Foreign Minister Ali Akbar Velayati explicitly warned on April 6, 2026: 'The unified command of the Resistance front views Bab al-Mandeb as it does Hormuz. If the White House dares to repeat its foolish mistakes, it will soon realize that the flow of global energy and trade can be disrupted with a single move.' Houthi military officials confirmed closure of Bab el-Mandeb would be among primary escalation options. This is not a hypothetical — it is a declared and operationally viable threat with a $1.8M+ prediction market already pricing the probability.

The Houthis' operational toolkit includes anti-ship cruise missiles, underwater drones, and loitering munitions — proven effective in 2023-24 during the Gaza conflict-linked Red Sea campaign. By April 2026, major carriers Maersk, CMA CGM, and Hapag-Lloyd had already rerouted vessels around the Cape of Good Hope, while war-risk insurance premiums had soared more than 1,000% since the conflict began.
1.3  India's Specific Exposure: The Pre-existing Vulnerability
India's energy dependency is structurally acute. The country imports more than 85% of its crude oil and over 90% of its LPG requirements. A substantial portion of these imports transit the Strait of Hormuz, and a significant share of India's exports to Europe — including textiles, pharmaceuticals, engineering goods, and chemicals — depend on the Red Sea–Bab el-Mandeb corridor. Maritime trade accounts for 95% of India's trade by volume and 70% by value.
The Hormuz blockade has already triggered severe domestic stress: the Indian rupee hit a record low of INR 94.79/USD on March 28, 2026; LPG prices crossed INR 4,000/cylinder on the black market; the Nifty 50 declined more than 10% in March alone; and foreign portfolio investors (FPIs) divested a record INR 1.61 lakh crore from Indian equities in the February-April period. Two Indian-flagged ships were targeted by Iranian gunfire on April 18 — prompting India to summon the Iranian ambassador — illustrating how quickly India's 'friendly nation' status can become transient.

