2.1  Scenario Architecture
SCENARIO A: Selective/Partial Closure  [Probability: 35–40%]
The Houthis conduct targeted strikes on US- and Israeli-flagged or -linked vessels, causing de facto commercial avoidance of the strait while not imposing a universal blockade. Most Asian-flagged vessels, including Indian ships with bilateral clearance, continue to operate — albeit with significant insurance cost increases and navigational risk.
Duration: 4–12 weeks. Oil through Bab el-Mandeb drops by 60–70%. Cape of Good Hope diversions increase freight costs by 40–60%. India experiences supply delays of 3–5 weeks on European-bound exports. LPG and crude supply constrained but not critically severed.

SCENARIO B: Full Operational Closure  [Probability: 40–45%]
The Houthis impose a near-complete blockade matching the Hormuz closure in scope and enforcement. Commercial shipping essentially ceases. This creates a true 'double chokepoint' scenario, cutting off 25% of global oil and gas supply simultaneously. Saudi Arabia's East-West Pipeline rerouting via Yanbu becomes irrelevant as Bab el-Mandeb — the exit for that pipeline's output — is also blocked.
Duration: 3–6 months. India's crude supply pipeline is critically disrupted. Oil prices surge to $120–$150/barrel. India's current account deficit widens to 4–5% of GDP. The rupee faces depreciation of 20–30%. Indian pharmaceutical exports to Europe and the US face existential logistics crises. Kharif agricultural season is compromised by fertiliser shortages.

SCENARIO C: Prolonged Strategic Closure (>6 Months)  [Probability: 15–25%]
A sustained closure lasting six months or more, representing a fundamental restructuring of global trade architecture. This scenario assumes failure of US-Iran diplomatic resolution, potential US military action against Houthi infrastructure, and escalatory Houthi counter-responses. Multiple global supply chains permanently reroute. Cape of Good Hope becomes the new normal for Asia-Europe shipping. IEA strategic reserves are exhausted. India enters a prolonged stagflationary environment.
India GDP contraction: 2.5–4.0% in FY 2026-27. Inflation exceeds 8–10%. The rupee potentially breaches INR 110/USD. Sovereign credit rating downgrades are probable. India's food security situation becomes a national emergency. The political economy faces severe internal stress, including potential social unrest.

