SECTION III: MULTI-DOMAIN IMPACT ASSESSMENT — INDIA

This section provides a comprehensive, sector-by-sector analysis of India's exposure to a Bab el-Mandeb closure, layered atop the existing Hormuz disruption. Twelve dimensions are examined in depth.
3.1  Energy Security & Petroleum
India is the world's third-largest oil importer and consumer, importing more than 85% of its crude oil needs and over 90% of its LPG. The Strait of Hormuz handled more than 40% of India's crude imports before the 2026 disruption; Bab el-Mandeb is the critical corridor for Indian crude exports and imports routed through Saudi Arabia's Red Sea coast (Yanbu) and for LPG from the Gulf.
Saudi Arabia's East-West Pipeline, which carries crude from Abqaiq to the Red Sea port of Yanbu at 7 million bpd capacity, represents Riyadh's key alternative to the Hormuz route. However, if Bab el-Mandeb is closed, this pipeline's output has no ocean outlet — nullifying the backup plan for both Saudi Arabia and Indian refineries sourcing from Yanbu. The 'double blockade' scenario thus leaves India without viable Gulf energy supply through any maritime route.
