The average price of India's crude basket surged from $69/barrel in February 2026 to $113/barrel in March — a 64% spike in a single month. Under a Bab el-Mandeb closure (Scenario B/C), analysts project this could reach $120–$200/barrel. A $10/barrel sustained increase widens India's current account deficit by 40–50 basis points. At $150/barrel — a plausible Scenario B outcome — the CAD could approach 4.5% of GDP, triggering a macro-balance-of-payments crisis reminiscent of 1991, though without that era's IMF bailout infrastructure being adequately equipped for the scale.
India's strategic petroleum reserves (SPR) offer approximately 9.5 days of import cover — manifestly insufficient against a multi-month blockade. The Indian government has attempted to diversify by resuming Iranian crude purchases (first since 2019), secured a 30-day US Treasury emergency waiver for stranded Russian oil cargoes, and is engaging Central Asian and African suppliers through alternative rail-sea routes including the International North-South Transport Corridor (INSTC).
ENERGY SECURITY VERDICT
India has no resilient contingency for a simultaneous Hormuz-Bab el-Mandeb closure lasting more than 3 months. SPR cover is inadequate, pipeline alternatives non-existent, and refinery feedstock diversification is insufficient at scale. The government must immediately escalate SPR capacity, accelerate INSTC operationalisation, and secure emergency crude access from non-Gulf sources including Russia, Brazil, and US shale producers.
3.2  Supply Chain & Shipping
India's maritime trade dependency is profound: 95% of trade by volume and 70% by value moves by sea. The Red Sea-Bab el-Mandeb-Suez corridor is India's primary trade artery to Europe, North Africa, and the Eastern Mediterranean. Its disruption forces vessels onto the Cape of Good Hope route, adding 10–14 days to transit time and $1.2–$1.8 million in additional fuel costs per voyage.
The impact cascades across all export-oriented sectors. Indian textiles and garments, engineering goods, leather products, and auto components destined for European markets face a 3–5 week delivery extension under partial closure, and 6–10 weeks under full closure. This renders just-in-time manufacturing supply chains — particularly in the automotive and electronics sectors — effectively dysfunctional. European buyers may invoke force majeure clauses or source locally, permanently redirecting procurement away from India.
Container freight rates on the India-Europe route have already risen significantly. Under Scenario B, they are projected to increase 300–500% above pre-crisis levels — compressing margins across India's export manufacturing sector and making Indian goods structurally uncompetitive against regional suppliers with shorter routing.
•	Shipping insurance premiums: Already up 1,000%+ since February 2026; Scenario B would see further 2–3x escalation.
•	Port congestion: Mundra, JNPT, and Nhava Sheva would face container pile-ups as European-bound cargo sits stranded.
•	EXIM credit stress: Indian exporters using letter-of-credit financing face working capital crises as delivery windows extend beyond payment terms.
•	Air freight substitution: Viable only for high-value goods (pharma, electronics components); adds 4–8x cost premium.
3.3  Food Security & Agriculture
Food security represents one of India's most urgent and least-discussed vulnerabilities in the Bab el-Mandeb scenario. India's Kharif planting season — which begins May-June and cannot be deferred — requires large volumes of fertilisers, principally diammonium phosphate (DAP) and muriate of potash (MOP), most of which are imported. With both Hormuz and Bab el-Mandeb disrupted, fertiliser shipments from Morocco, Jordan, Saudi Arabia, and the former Soviet states through Red Sea routes face severe delays.
The International Fund for Agricultural Development (IFAD) has warned that the existing Hormuz disruption has 'had immediate repercussions for fertilizers, fuel and other agricultural inputs,' with cascading effects on planting, farm-gate prices, and rural incomes. A Bab el-Mandeb closure would compound this. Projections indicate up to 45 million additional people could face acute food insecurity globally in 2026, with South Asia — and specifically the Indian subcontinent — particularly exposed.
