3.4  Petrochemicals & Chemical Industry
India's petrochemical sector is deeply import-dependent for feedstocks including naphtha, liquefied petroleum gas (LPG), propane, and butane — much of which originates in the Gulf. The Reliance Industries complex at Jamnagar (the world's largest refinery complex), ONGC's facilities, and the entire downstream plastics, fertiliser, and synthetic fibre industry depend on uninterrupted feedstock supply.
LPG disruption is particularly acute given its dual household-industrial role. The existing Hormuz blockade has already pushed Indian LPG cylinder prices above INR 4,000 on the black market. Long queues at distribution centres, a 30x surge in induction stove sales on Amazon, and government authorisation for restaurants to use biomass fuel illustrate the human dimension of this crisis. A Bab el-Mandeb closure would eliminate Saudi Arabian LPG via Yanbu — the remaining viable supply corridor — making the shortage systemic.
India's petrochemical export competitiveness — particularly in polymers, synthetic rubber, and specialty chemicals — would also be compromised as higher feedstock costs and shipping disruptions erode margins. The downstream impact extends to the packaging, construction, automotive, and consumer goods sectors.
3.5  Financial Markets & Macroeconomic Stability
India's financial markets are already registering severe stress from the Hormuz disruption. The Nifty 50 fell more than 10% in March 2026 — the worst monthly decline since COVID-19. Foreign portfolio investors (FPIs) divested a record INR 1.61 lakh crore from Indian equities between late February and April. The rupee hit INR 94.79/USD on March 28, 2026 — a record low — forcing the RBI to deploy currency intervention and impose hedging restrictions on banks.
Under a Bab el-Mandeb closure (Scenario B), the financial market transmission channels are severe and self-reinforcing. The oil price shock widens the current account deficit, which weakens the rupee, which raises the cost of rupee-denominated debt service on foreign currency obligations, which elevates sovereign risk premiums, which triggers further FPI outflows, which further weakens the rupee — a classic vicious cycle of external stress.
