The stagflationary combination — slowing growth with accelerating inflation — is particularly dangerous for India because it eliminates the usual policy tool. The RBI cannot cut rates to stimulate growth (as this would exacerbate inflation and rupee depreciation) nor raise rates to control inflation (as this would choke growth and increase debt servicing costs). The government faces a similarly constrained fiscal space. India is at risk of entering a policy trap not seen since the 1991 balance-of-payments crisis.
3.7  Pharmaceuticals & Healthcare Supply Chains
India is the world's pharmacy — supplying approximately 20–25% of global generic medicines by volume and serving 60+ countries. Indian pharmaceutical exports reached $28 billion in FY 2024-25, with the US ($9 billion), EU ($5 billion), and Africa ($4 billion) as the principal markets. The Europe-bound and US-bound shipments primarily transit the Red Sea-Bab el-Mandeb-Suez Canal corridor. A closure imposes immediate logistical crisis on this pipeline.
The pharmaceutical supply chain has a unique time-sensitivity dimension: many medicines have strict cold-chain requirements, limited shelf lives, and regulatory stockpile requirements in destination markets. Extended transit times through the Cape of Good Hope — adding 10–14 days — may breach regulatory dossier specifications for certain temperature-sensitive biologics and injectables. Drug shortages in European and African markets for Indian-manufactured generics would likely emerge within 4–6 weeks of full closure.
Concurrently, India's domestic pharmaceutical manufacturers depend on Active Pharmaceutical Ingredient (API) imports from China, much of which transits through the Bab el-Mandeb in the Asia-Europe-returning direction. A closure in both directions would thus compress both India's export revenue and its domestic API input supply — a double-sided supply chain attack.
PHARMACEUTICAL SECTOR CRITICAL RISK
The pharma sector faces simultaneous threats: export logistics disruption (Bab el-Mandeb closure reduces export volumes by 30–50% in Scenario B), API import compression (China-origin inputs delayed), and price competition from alternative suppliers. India must accelerate domestic API manufacturing self-sufficiency and seek emergency air-freight corridors for critical medicines.
3.8  Electronics, Semiconductors & Technology Supply Chains
India's electronics sector — growing at approximately 18–20% annually under the PLI scheme, with ambitions to become a $300 billion industry by 2026 — is deeply integrated into the Asia-Europe supply chain that transits Bab el-Mandeb. Consumer electronics imports from China, semiconductor components from Taiwan and South Korea, and specialised industrial electronics from Germany and Japan all depend on the Red Sea corridor.
The PLI-driven mobile phone and consumer electronics assembly in India depends on components — display modules, memory chips, camera sensors — sourced from East Asian manufacturers. Disruption to the Bab el-Mandeb route, even in the Asia-outbound direction, means delays in inbound component shipments reaching Indian assembly facilities. This threatens India's nascent semiconductor and electronics manufacturing ambitions at a critical stage of their development.
India's nascent EV supply chain — importing lithium-ion batteries, battery management systems, and permanent magnets from China and South Korea — is similarly at risk. The Cape of Good Hope diversion adds 3–4 weeks to component transit times, creating production halts in assembly facilities that have limited inventory buffer.
Positively, the crisis accelerates India's push to diversify electronics supply chains away from Chinese dependence. Indian firms and the government are likely to deepen ties with ASEAN, Japan, and US suppliers who may offer alternative routing via Pacific Ocean routes (bypassing Bab el-Mandeb entirely). This structural pivot — while painful in the short term — aligns with India's long-term supply chain resilience agenda.
3.9  Remittances, Gulf Diaspora & Human Capital
Approximately 10 million Indians reside in Gulf Cooperation Council (GCC) states — the UAE, Saudi Arabia, Kuwait, Qatar, Bahrain, and Oman. Their remittances totalled over $40 billion in 2024, making the Gulf the single largest source of India's remittance inflows, which in turn comprise roughly one-third of India's total inflow. These remittances are a critical stabiliser for India's balance of payments and a primary income source for households in Kerala, Telangana, Uttar Pradesh, and Bihar.
The 2026 Iran war has caused mass departure of expatriate workers from Gulf states hit by Iranian drone strikes on civilian infrastructure. Dubai, which hosts the largest Indian expatriate community, has seen significant population outflows. If the crisis escalates — with Bab el-Mandeb closure cutting off Gulf states from global supply chains and triggering economic contraction — Indian Gulf workers face mass unemployment, forced repatriation, and loss of income. The repatriation of 500,000–2 million Indian workers from the Gulf would create both a domestic unemployment shock and a humanitarian crisis, while simultaneously removing approximately $12–20 billion from India's annual remittance inflow.
3.10  Cryptocurrency Markets & Digital Finance
India's crypto market has matured significantly, with Bitcoin accounting for 9.2% of investor holdings and 17.4% of trading activity. The Iran war's first quarter triggered sharp initial corrections in crypto markets, followed by recovery faster than in previous cycles — a pattern consistent with crypto's evolving role as a geopolitical hedge asset.
The Bab el-Mandeb scenario presents a dual dynamic for crypto. On the safe-haven demand side: as the rupee weakens, equities sell off, and traditional banking channels face stress, Indian retail and institutional investors are increasingly allocating to Bitcoin and Ethereum as dollar-denominated stores of value outside the domestic financial system. This mirrors the Bitcoin demand surge observed in Turkey and Argentina during currency crises.
On the systemic risk side: energy price shocks directly impact Bitcoin mining economics, as mining is energy-intensive. If Indian electricity costs surge due to fuel oil and LNG price spikes, domestic mining becomes economically non-viable, redirecting India's nascent crypto-mining sector offshore. Additionally, if the US Treasury extends sanctions enforcement to crypto channels used by Iran or Houthi-linked entities, Indian crypto exchanges face compliance risk that could trigger regulatory crackdowns.
Iran has historically used cryptocurrencies to circumvent sanctions. The Bab el-Mandeb crisis scenario could see Iran-linked actors attempting to use Indian crypto infrastructure as a routing mechanism — creating regulatory and reputational risk for India's fintech sector. The Financial Intelligence Unit (FIU-IND)'s new AML compliance norms (early 2026) provide some safeguard, but enforcement capacity remains limited.
From a global perspective, the crisis reinforces the argument for decentralised digital currencies as alternatives to the dollar-denominated SWIFT system that US sanctions leverage. This benefits BRICS-aligned digital currency initiatives — including proposals for a common BRICS payment system that India has ambiguously engaged with. The longer the crisis persists, the stronger the structural argument for crypto and CBDC alternatives to dollar dependence becomes.
3.11  The Bretton Woods System: Legitimacy Under Siege
The dual chokepoint crisis of 2026 is exposing fundamental fissures in the post-1944 Bretton Woods international economic order — the system built on US dollar hegemony, the IMF and World Bank as lenders of last resort, and the WTO as the rule-based trade arbiter. Each of these pillars faces acute stress.
The Petrodollar Architecture
The Bretton Woods system's survival past 1971 was premised on the petrodollar agreement — oil priced and settled in US dollars globally, recycled through US financial markets. The Hormuz closure has disrupted physical oil flows, but the larger systemic risk is the disruption of dollar-denominated oil settlements. China's decision to allow yuan-settled crude purchases from Iran and Russia — accelerated by the crisis — represents a structural fracture in the petrodollar system. If Saudi Arabia, under pressure from a Bab el-Mandeb closure affecting its Red Sea exports, also moves toward yuan-settled contracts with China, the petrodollar architecture begins to fragment in earnest.
IMF & World Bank Capacity
The IMF has already released 400 million barrels of strategic reserves through the IEA (including UK participation) and is coordinating emergency lending facilities for oil-importing developing nations facing balance-of-payments stress. However, the scale of the 2026 crisis — potentially affecting 25% of global energy flows — exceeds the IMF's conventional response capacity. India, as a significant economy with a large external financing need, may require IMF support under a prolonged Scenario C. However, the optics of an IMF programme — historically associated with conditionality and loss of policy sovereignty — would be politically toxic for the Modi government, creating a dangerous gap between financial necessity and political feasibility.
WTO & Trade Rules Disintegration
The crisis is accelerating the fragmentation of the WTO-based multilateral trade order. Emergency export restrictions on food, pharmaceuticals, and critical minerals — already being imposed by multiple countries — technically violate WTO disciplines but are politically inevitable. India's own potential fertiliser export restrictions (to protect domestic supply) and pharmaceuticals export curbs (to prioritise domestic healthcare) would likely follow. The WTO's dispute resolution mechanism, already weakened by US blocking of Appellate Body appointments, is effectively non-functional as a crisis management tool.
BRETTON WOODS ASSESSMENT
The 2026 crisis is accelerating three secular trends: (1) de-dollarisation of energy trade; (2) bifurcation of the global financial system into US-aligned and BRICS-aligned blocs; and (3) erosion of multilateral institutional authority. India's strategic interest lies in preserving elements of the rules-based order that benefit it (maritime law, WTO tariff bindings, IMF lender capacity) while avoiding entrapment in a bloc confrontation that limits its strategic autonomy. This is an extraordinarily difficult tightrope to maintain.
3.12  Trust in Global Institutions & Regime Legitimacy
The 2026 crisis is generating a profound legitimacy challenge for international institutions and the 'rules-based international order' — a phrase that India has itself championed as an alternative to great power unilateralism. The specific trust dynamics relevant to India are multi-directional.
First, the US-Israeli military operation against Iran — including the assassination of a sovereign state's Supreme Leader — has been condemned across the Global South as a violation of the UN Charter's sovereign equality principle. China and Russia vetoed a UN Security Council resolution on the Hormuz strait in April 2026. India's silence on this action, combined with PM Modi's February 26 Knesset address, has damaged its credibility as a voice of the Global South within forums like the G20, SCO, and BRICS.
Second, the failure of Western-led maritime coalitions to reopen the Strait of Hormuz or deter Houthi action at Bab el-Mandeb has exposed the limits of US power projection in contested maritime spaces. This has strategic implications for India's own dependence on US security assurances in the Indo-Pacific — the Quad framework's value to India is partly premised on US credibility as a maritime security provider. That credibility is being tested.
Third, Pakistan's emergence as the primary US-Iran back-channel intermediary — mediating the conditional ceasefire from Islamabad — represents a direct blow to India's regional standing. India, which has systematically tried to isolate Pakistan diplomatically, finds its rival elevated to a peacemaker role in the most consequential geopolitical crisis of the decade.

SECTION IV: INDIA'S DIPLOMATIC POSTURE & PROBABLE ALIGNMENTS

4.1  The Structural Dilemma: Balancing Between Blocs
India's traditional foreign policy posture — strategic autonomy, non-alignment, multi-vector engagement — is being severely stress-tested. The country simultaneously needs: US sanctions waivers to purchase Russian and Iranian oil; Chinese acquiescence to India-flagged vessels transiting a crisis zone where China has disproportionate influence; Iranian goodwill to allow safe passage; and Western market access for its pharmaceutical and textile exports. No single alignment satisfies all of these needs simultaneously.
PM Modi's February 26, 2026 Knesset address — three days before Operation Epic Fury began — placed India visually and symbolically in the pro-Israel camp at the worst possible moment. The address, while not explicitly endorsing military action, narrowed India's diplomatic credibility as a neutral mediator. As one analyst noted: 'The space for diplomatic maneuvering has shrunk considerably.' Iran subsequently initially labelled India a 'friendly nation' for Hormuz transit purposes — reflecting that bilateral relationships survived — but the April 18 targeting of Indian-flagged ships and India's need to summon the Iranian ambassador revealed the fragility of this status.
4.2  India's Probable Diplomatic Actions Under Bab el-Mandeb Closure
Bilateral Engagement with Houthis and Iran
India has neither recognised the Houthis as a government nor maintained formal channels, but it has demonstrated willingness to engage through informal back-channels when necessary. Under a Bab el-Mandeb closure, India would likely seek explicit 'safe passage' assurances for Indian-flagged or Indian-charted vessels, potentially leveraging its Muslim-majority population's symbolic significance, its historical non-interventionist posture, and its economic ties with Yemen's neighbours.
The precedent of Muslim-owned and Turkish-operated vessels successfully transiting Hormuz by broadcasting their identity demonstrates that the Houthis and Iran are making political rather than purely military decisions about whom to target. India could seek to activate this logic — positioning itself explicitly as a non-belligerent developing nation without alliance obligations to either the US or Israel.
Engagement with China
China has demonstrated its willingness to allow its flagged vessels preferred transit through Hormuz — a status that India could partly leverage by chartering Chinese vessels or by coordinating with China on joint diplomatic pressure. The irony is profound: to protect its trade from disruption by Iran's allies, India may need to coordinate with China — its primary strategic competitor. The Bab el-Mandeb scenario thus creates a structural incentive for India-China pragmatic cooperation that contradicts the prevailing Quad-aligned strategic narrative.
Non-Participation in US Naval Coalition
India has already 'chosen to negotiate bilaterally with Iran for safe passage instead of joining Washington's proposed naval coalition — a deliberate act of distance,' as characterised by Verisk Maplecroft. This posture would be maintained under a Bab el-Mandeb scenario. Joining the US naval coalition would provoke Houthi and Iranian retaliation against Indian shipping, reversing the 'friendly nation' status that provides India's only current supply security. The calculus strongly favours continued non-participation, even at the cost of bilateral friction with Washington.
SCO and BRICS Engagement
India would intensify diplomatic engagement through the Shanghai Cooperation Organisation (SCO) and BRICS frameworks — both of which include Iran as members — to seek collective pressure for restraint and reopening of maritime corridors. This multilateral framing allows India to press for corridor reopening without appearing to align with the US position.
