The 1973 Arab Oil Embargo is the closest historical analogue for the oil price shock dimension. That crisis triggered the collapse of fixed exchange rates under Bretton Woods II (Smithsonian Agreement), a global recession, and permanently reshaped energy policy in all major importing nations. The 2026 crisis is occurring against an already-stressed global economic backdrop — elevated debt levels, high inflation, and weakened multilateral institutions — making the systemic shock absorption capacity significantly lower than in 1973.
The 1991 India balance-of-payments crisis — triggered partly by Gulf War-related oil price spikes and remittance disruptions — serves as the domestic precedent. India then had 15 days of import cover and required an emergency gold pledge to the Bank of England and a hasty IMF programme. The structural vulnerabilities are eerily similar in 2026, though India's foreign exchange reserves ($640 billion as of early 2026) provide significantly more buffer — the question is how rapidly that buffer is depleted under a prolonged dual chokepoint scenario.

CONCLUSION

The closure of the Bab el-Mandeb Strait, in the context of the ongoing Strait of Hormuz disruption, represents the single most consequential external risk to India in the post-independence era. It is not a hypothetical tail risk — it is a declared operational threat from a credible non-state actor with demonstrated capability, motivated by a live regional conflict involving a nuclear-threshold state.
For India, the crisis arrives at a moment of structural vulnerability: high oil import dependency, limited SPR coverage, an already-weakening currency, record FPI outflows, and a diplomatic positioning that has narrowed its room for manoeuvre precisely when maximum flexibility is needed. The country that has most loudly proclaimed its emergence as a global power is proving, as one commentator observed, 'too inconsequential to influence the warmakers — and too weak to be spared its effects.'
Yet India also possesses unique assets in this crisis: its economic scale makes it too important to fully antagonise for either the US or Iran; its non-belligerent status is accepted (albeit conditionally) by all parties; its position in the Indian Ocean Region gives it geographical centrality to any solution; and its domestic market's demand provides economic leverage with oil-exporting nations.
The path forward demands a calibrated, interest-driven foreign policy that prioritises energy security above alliance solidarity, exploits every multilateral forum to advance a 'civilian shipping immunity' norm, and begins the long-term structural work of reducing India's chokepoint dependency. The immediate crisis is manageable if India acts decisively. The structural vulnerability will persist until India treats maritime supply security as a core pillar of national security — not an afterthought.

FINAL RISK RATING
OVERALL RISK TO INDIA: CRITICAL (Score 9.1/10 under Scenario B; 9.7/10 under Scenario C). Immediate action required across energy, diplomatic, financial, food security, and pharmaceutical domains. This is not a situation where 'wait and watch' is a viable policy posture.

